'''Grzegorz of Stawiszyn''' ({{lang-pl|Grzegorz ze Stawiszyna}}; 1481&ndash;1540), was a [[Poles|Polish]] [[philosopher]] and [[theologian]] of the mid 16th century, [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] of the [[University of Krakow]]  in the years 1538-1540.<ref>[http://www.uj.edu.pl/dispatch.jsp?item=uniwersytet/historia/poczet.jsp&lang=en  Past Rectors of the Jagiellonian University of Kraków] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710133051/http://www.uj.edu.pl/dispatch.jsp?item=uniwersytet%2Fhistoria%2Fpoczet.jsp&lang=en |date=2009-07-10 }} Brief history at JU official website.</ref> 

Grzegorz was born in [[Stawiszyn]] in 1481. He was an adherent of [[Nominalism]], a [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]] view in philosophy, revived in [[western Europe]] at the turn of the sixteenth century thanks to French philosopher [[Jacques Lefèvre d'Étaples]] (''Faber Stapulensis''). Once Nominalism reappeared in [[Kraków]] and began taking precedence over [[Thomism]] and [[Scotism]], Grzegorz of Stawiszyn, a Kraków professor, published Jacques d'Étaples works including his commentaries to works by [[Aristotle]], beginning in 1510.<ref>[[Władysław Tatarkiewicz]], ''Zarys dziejów filozofii w Polsce'' (A Brief History of Philosophy in Poland), [in the series:] Historia nauki polskiej w monografiach (''History of Polish Learning in Monographs''), [volume] XXXII, Kraków, Polska Akademia Umiejętności ([[Polish Academy of Learning]]), 1948. This monograph draws from pertinent sections in earlier editions of the author's Historia filozofii (History of Philosophy), pp. 6–7.</ref> As rector, Grzegorz introduced first reforms toward leaving the scholasticism of [[Peter of Spain (author)|Peter of Spain]] at the University of Krakow beginning 1538, and replacing it with the [[Renaissance]] [[Aristotelianism]], including classes in logic based on Dialectics of Jan Caesarius.<ref>Filozofia, [http://www.pod.pisz.pl/8-reforma-uk  Grzegorz ze Stawiszyna]</ref> He died in [[Krakow]].

