'''Stefan Lorenz Sorgner''' is a German metahumanist philosopher,<ref>{{cite web |title=Selak, Marija |url=http://bib.irb.hr/prikazi-rad?lang=en&rad=744704 |accessdate=June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bu.edu/paideia/existenz/volumes/Vol.8-2Ferrando.pdf |title=Posthumanism, Transhumanism, Antihumanism, Metahumanism, and New Materialisms |accessdate=June 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501113445/http://www.bu.edu/paideia/existenz/volumes/Vol.8-2Ferrando.pdf |archivedate=2015-05-01 |df= }}</ref> a [[Nietzsche]] scholar,<ref>{{cite web|author=Prof. H. James Birx in Philosophy Now |url=http://www.philosophynow.org/issue29/Nietzsche_Studies_I |title=Sorgner and Nietzsche |publisher=Philosophy Now |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Several Scholars |url=http://www.marquette.edu/mupress/sorgner_nietzsche.shtml |title=Comments on Sorgner's Nietzsche Interpretation|publisher=University of Marquette Press |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Russell Blackford |url=http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/print/3636/ |title=Nietzsche and European Posthumanisms |publisher=IEET|date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref> a [[Philosophy of music|philosopher of music]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Alber Verlag |url= http://www.verlag-alber.de/reihen/uebersicht_html?k_onl_struktur=2878350 |publisher=Alber Verlag |title = Book Series: Philosophy of Music|date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=University of Chicago Press |url= http://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3750659.html|title=Music in German Philosophy |publisher=University of Chicago Press |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref> and an authority in the field of [[Ethics of technology|ethics of]] [[emerging technologies]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Russell Blackford |url=http://jetpress.org/v21/blackford2.htm |title=Editorial |publisher=Journal of Evolution and Technology|date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=University of Manchester |url=http://www.isei.manchester.ac.uk/research/conferences/beyondthebody/ |title=Beyond the Body |publisher=University of Manchester |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-29}}</ref><ref name="KAIST">{{cite web |author=KAIST |url=http://www.icists.org/program/ |title=Shaping the Future |publisher=KAIST |date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629132041/http://www.icists.org/program/ |archivedate=2015-06-29 |df= }}</ref>
==Life== Sorgner was born on 15 October 1973 in [[Wetzlar]] (Germany). He studied philosophy at [[King's College London]] (BA), the [[University of Durham]] (MA by thesis; examiners: [[David E. Cooper]], Durham; David Owen, Southampton), the Justus-Liebig-Universität Gießen and the Friedrich-Schiller-Universität Jena (Dr. phil.; Examiners: [[Wolfgang Welsch]], Jena; [[Gianni Vattimo]], Turin).<ref>{{cite web |author=stefan lorenz sorgner |url=https://uni-erlangen.academia.edu/StefanLorenzSorgner |title=Stefan Lorenz Sorgner &#124; Friedrich-Alexander-University Erlangen-Nuremberg - Academia.edu |publisher=Uni-erlangen.academia.edu |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2011-01-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ct798hpW?url=http://uni-erlangen.academia.edu/StefanLorenzSorgner |archivedate=2012-12-13 |df= }}</ref> He taught philosophy and ethics at the Universities of [[Giessen]], [[Jena]], [[Erfurt]] and [[Erlangen]].<ref name="Gesch.med.uni-erlangen.de">{{cite web |url=http://www.gesch.med.uni-erlangen.de/mitarbeiterinnen/stefan-sorgner.shtml |title=Institut für Geschichte und Ethik der Medizin: Stefan Lorenz Sorgner |publisher=Gesch.med.uni-erlangen.de |language=German |date= |accessdate=2011-01-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ct79nxKA?url=http://www.gesch.med.uni-erlangen.de/mitarbeiterinnen/stefan-sorgner.shtml |archivedate=2012-12-13 |df= }}</ref> Currently, he teaches at a US Liberal Arts College, [[John Cabot University]].<ref>http://www.johncabot.edu/directory/Faculty_Form.aspx?IdFaculty=578</ref> Sorgner is a member of several editorial and advisory boards.<ref name="Gesch.med.uni-erlangen.de"/>
==Nietzsche, posthumanism and transhumanism== In issue 20(1) of the [[Journal of Evolution and Technology]], Sorgner's article “Nietzsche, the Overhuman, and Transhumanism” was published in which he shows that there are significant similarities between Nietzsche's concept of the overhuman and the concept of the [[posthuman]] according to the view of some transhumanists.<ref name="Blackford 2010a">{{cite journal| last=Blackford | first=Russel | authorlink = Russel Blackford |title = Editorial: Nietzsche and European Posthumanisms |year = 2010 |url = http://jetpress.org/v21/blackford.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> His interpretation brought about a response both among Nietzsche scholars as well as among transhumanists. The editors of the [[Journal of Evolution and Technology]] dedicated a special issue to the question concerning the relationship between [[transhumanism]], Nietzsche and European posthumanist philosophies ([[posthumanism]]). Vol. 21 Issue 1 – January 2010 of the [[Journal of Evolution and Technology]] was entitled "Nietzsche and European Posthumanisms"<ref name="Blackford 2010a"/><ref name="Sorgner 2009">{{cite journal| last=Sorgner | first=Stefan Lorenz | authorlink = Stefan Lorenz Sorgner |title = Nietzsche, the Overhuman, and Transhumanism |year = 2009 |url = http://jetpress.org/v20/sorgner.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> and it included responses to Sorgner's article, for example by [[Max More]],<ref name="More 2010">{{cite journal| last=More | first=Max | authorlink = Max More |title = The Overhuman in the Transhuman |year = 2010 |url = http://jetpress.org/v21/more.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> [[Michael Hauskeller]].<ref name="Hauskeller 2010">{{cite journal| last=Hauskeller | first=Michael | authorlink = Michael Hauskeller |title = Nietzsche, the Overhuman and the Posthuman: A Reply to Stefan Sorgner |year = 2010 |url = http://jetpress.org/v21/hauskeller.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> Due to the intense debate, the editors of the journal decided to give Sorgner the chance to react to the articles.<ref name="Blackford 2010b">{{cite journal| last=Blackford | first=Russel | authorlink = Russel Blackford |title = Editorial |year = 2010 |url = http://jetpress.org/v21/blackford2.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> In vol. 21 Issue 2 – October 2010, Sorgner replied to the various responses in his article "Beyond Humanism: Reflections on Trans- and Posthumanism".<ref name="Sorgner 2010">{{cite journal| last=Sorgner | first=Stefan Lorenz | authorlink = Stefan Lorenz Sorgner |title = Beyond Humanism: Reflections on Trans- and Posthumanism |year = 2010 |url = http://jetpress.org/v21/sorgner.htm| accessdate=2011-01-27}}</ref> In addition, herein he also put forward some aspects of his own philosophical position which was strongly influenced by his teacher [[Gianni Vattimo]].<ref>{{cite web |author=PHILOSOPHIE.CH |url=http://www.philosophie.ch/events/single.php?action=date&eventid=1522 |title=A weak Nietzschean transhumanism |publisher=www.philosophie.ch |date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714182312/http://www.philosophie.ch/events/single.php?action=date&eventid=1522 |archivedate=2015-07-14 |df= }}</ref> He accepts [[Vattimo]]'s pensiero debole, but criticises [[Vattimo]]'s understanding of the history of the weakening of being.<ref name="Beatrix Vogel">{{cite web|author=Beatrix Vogel |url= http://www.verlag-alber.de/vorschau/details_html?k_tnr=48655&k_onl_struktur=712809/|title= Umwertung der Menschenwürde |publisher=Alber Verlag|date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14 }}</ref> As an alternative, Sorgner suggests a this-worldly, naturalist and perspectivist interpretation of the world, which he explained in more detail in his 2010 monograph "Menschenwürde nach Nietzsche: Die Geschichte eines Begriffs" (WBG, Darmstadt 2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wbg-wissenverbindet.de/WBGShop/php/Proxy.php?purl=/wbg/products/show,8533.html |title=WBG - Shop - Menschenwürde nach Nietzsche |publisher=Wbg-wissenverbindet.de |language=German |date= |accessdate=2011-01-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719113315/http://www.wbg-wissenverbindet.de/WBGShop/php/Proxy.php?purl=%2Fwbg%2Fproducts%2Fshow%2C8533.html |archivedate=2011-07-19 |df= }}</ref> Sorgner regards "[[Nihilism]]", as described by Nietzsche, "entirely a gain":<ref>Stefan Lorenz Sorgner, ''Menschenwürde nach Nietzsche'', Darmstadt WBG, 2010, p. 239: "durchaus als Gewinn".</ref> „From the perspective of my perspectivism, this also means that the prevalent conception of human dignity has no higher status in hitting truth as correspondence to reality than the conceptions of [[Adolf Hitler]] or [[Pol Pot]]."<ref>Stefan Lorenz Sorgner, ''Menschenwürde nach Nietzsche'', Darmstadt WBG, 2010, p. 242: "Dies bedeutet auch, dass dem vorherrschenden Konzept der Menschenwürde aus der Perspektive des Perspektivismus kein höherer Status hinsichtlich der Erkenntnis der Wahrheit in Korrespondenz zur Wirklichkeit zukommt als den Konzeptionen Adolf Hitlers oder Pol Pots."</ref> After bioethicists, and transhumanists had discussed the relationship between Nietzsche and transhumanism, the debate was taken up by some leading Nietzsche scholars: [[Keith Ansell-Pearson]], [[Paul Loeb]] and [[Babette Babich]] wrote responses in the journal the Agonist which is being published by the Nietzsche Circle New York.<ref name="The Agonist">{{cite journal| last=Tuncel | first=Yunus | authorlink = Yunus Tuncel |title = Nietzsche and Trans- and Metahumanism |year = 2012 |url = http://www.nietzschecircle.com/agonist.html| accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref> Sorgner's perspectivist metahumanism and in particular his monograph "Menschenwürde nach Nietzsche" (WBG 2010) was dealt with in a symposium organised by the Nietzsche Forum Munich which had been co-founded by [[Thomas Mann]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nietzsche-forum-muenchen.de/aktuell/einladungen/251012_raetsel_mensch.html |title=Humans as riddle: Human dignity after/according to Nietzsche |publisher=Nietzsche Forum Munich |language=German |date= |accessdate=2012-12-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402133803/http://www.nietzsche-forum-muenchen.de/aktuell/einladungen/251012_raetsel_mensch.html |archivedate=2015-04-02 |df= }}</ref> Leading German philosophers, e.g. [[Annemarie Pieper]], responded to Sorgner's radical suggestions concerning the need to revise the prevalent conception of human dignity at this event. In May 2013, the weekly newspaper [[Die Zeit]] published an interview with Sorgner in which several of his suggestions concerning human dignity, emerging technologies and trans- and posthumanism were summarized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/2013/20/transhumanismus-philosoph-stefan-lorenz-sorgner |title= Hirnschrittmacher für alle |publisher= Die Zeit |language=German |date= |accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref> In Autumn 2014, an essay collection entitled "Umwertung der Menschenwürde" (edited by Beatrix Vogel) was published by Alber Verlag in which leading international theologians, philosophers, and ethicists wrote critical replies to Sorgner's suggestions concerning the notion "human dignity".<ref name="Beatrix Vogel"/> Sorgner has been an invited and keynote speaker at many important events and conferences, e.g. Phil.cologne,<ref>{{cite web |author=Phil.cologne |url=http://www.philcologne.de/mitwirkende/detail/pers/sorgner-stefan-lorenz/ |publisher=Phil.cologne |title=Phil.cologne 2015 |date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711050755/http://www.philcologne.de/mitwirkende/detail/pers/sorgner-stefan-lorenz/ |archivedate=2015-07-11 |df= }}</ref> [[TED (conference)|TED]],<ref>{{cite web|author=TEDx |url= http://tedxtalks.ted.com/video/Suggestions-for-a-Posthuman-Zoo;search%3ASorgner|publisher=TEDx |title = Rules for a (Post-)Human) Zoo|date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14 }}</ref> and the World Humanities Forum, ICISTS-KAIST.<ref name="KAIST"/> According to Prof. Dr. Zimmmermann of the Identity Foundation, a recently set-up German private think tank, Sorgner is “Germany’s leading post- and transhumanist philosopher” („Deutschlands führender post- und transhumanistischer Philosoph“).<ref>{{cite web|author=Identity Foundation |url= http://www.identity-foundation.de/images/stories/downloads/philcologne/P150054_Booklet%20philCologne_RZ_150416.pdf|publisher=Identity foundation |title = Phil.cologne 2015|date=2015-06-14 |accessdate=2015-06-14}}</ref>
